The Fragility of a Flat World
The world is flat!
Said Thomas Friedman, a columnist. Friedman chose this highly provocative title for his best-selling book to make people aware of the astonishing impact of technology on the global economy.
Distances are shrinking.
Geographic barriers can no longer easily provide security.
Manufacturing workers and high-tech professionals in Europe and the United States have all had to face the challenges of global competition.
When Western consumers call local companies, the employees they speak with may be far away in India.
Skeptics have pointed out the limitations of Friedman's metaphor.
As someone said, the world is not flat, but rather "uneven".
Topographic maps of global economic activity show peaks of prosperity and valleys of scarcity.
Not only that, distance has by no means lost its significance.
Even neighboring countries with relatively low tariff barriers, such as Canada and the United States, have far more domestic trade than cross-border trade.
Seattle and Vancouver are geographically close, but Vancouver's trade with the more distant Toronto is far greater than its trade with the nearby Seattle.
Despite such criticisms, Friedman still put forward an important point.
Globalization can be defined as mutual dependence between different continents, a history as long as human history, witnessing the migration of races and religions, as well as the trade along the ancient Silk Road between medieval Europe and Asia.
But today's globalization is different, developing faster and more deeply.
After the first transatlantic telegraph cable was laid in 1868, Europe and America could communicate within just one minute.
In 1919, economist John Maynard Keynes described British people living in London ordering goods from all over the world by telephone, and then sitting at home waiting to receive them in the afternoon.
However, Keynes's British people were a special case of the wealthy.
Today, hundreds of millions of people around the world can buy products from all over the world at their local supermarkets.
Similarly, 20 years ago, instant global communication emerged, but it was economically beyond the reach of the majority of people.
Now, almost anyone can walk into an internet café and gain access to capabilities that were once only available to governments, multinational corporations, and a few individuals or organizations with large budgets.
The significant decline in the costs of computing, communication, and transportation has made technology increasingly accessible.
Just 10 years ago, two-thirds of internet users were concentrated in the United States.
Today, internet users in the United States account for less than a quarter of the global user base.
Knowledge is power, and today the number of people who have access to information has reached the highest level in human history.
Non-state actors now possess capabilities that were once exclusively held by governments.
The position of the nation-state as a principal actor in world politics will not change in the near future, but it must learn to share this vast stage with a broader range of participants, including organizations such as the Oxford Committee for Famine Relief, celebrities like Bono, and transnational terrorist networks such as Al-Qaeda.
However, this process of flattening is reversible.
Similar situations have occurred in the past.
In 1914, the world economy was highly integrated, but in the following 30 years, the interdependence of economies around the world continuously declined.
It wasn't until 1970 that the global economy recovered to the level of integration it had once experienced, although it was still heavily divided by the Iron Curtain at that time.
World War I was the catalyst for this reversal; during both world wars and the Cold War, people witnessed a decline in economic globalization and an increase in military globalization.
This reflected deeper issues caused by the development of the economy in the 19th century, such as domestic inequality.
Politics failed to adapt to economic development, resulting in abnormal ideologies—fascism and communism—reaching their peak; this pathological development concept caused the fragmentation of nations and the world.
The welfare state system in the West after World War II provided a safety net for those harmed by economic changes, encouraging them to accept the rewards brought by international economic interdependence.
Some analysts argue that today's role played by China is very similar to that of Germany in the 20th century.
They are rising powers troubled by domestic inequality, constantly developing in a nationalist direction, challenging the dominant powers, and ultimately triggering world wars that reverse the progress of economic globalization.
Although the economies of the United States and China are highly interdependent today, the economies of Britain and Germany were similarly interdependent before 1914.
However, such reasoning is not sound.
After 1900, Germany's industrial production had surpassed that of Britain.
However, even if China maintains its current high growth rate, its economy is unlikely to catch up with the United States within at least 20 years.
What poses a greater threat to the flat world is probably the non-state and transnational forces unleashed by the spread of technology.
On September 11, 2001, a non-state network killed more Americans in an unannounced attack than the Japanese government did in its Pearl Harbor attack in 1941.
I refer to this phenomenon as the privatization of war.
If such forces were to acquire nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world would undergo tremendous changes.
At that time, it would become even more difficult for people and goods to cross national borders.
If the aforementioned forces disrupted the oil exports from the Persian Gulf, which holds two-thirds of the world's oil reserves, a global economic depression similar to that of the 1930s could further strengthen the power of protectionism.
Technology and policy are the two major driving forces of globalization.
So far, policies have further reinforced the flattening effect of technology.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States holds a leading position in promoting policies to remove barriers.
However, the events described above may reverse such policies.
Certain critics of globalization may be willing to see such an outcome.
But such an outcome, as we saw after 1914, would lead to the worst situation in two areas¾the trend of economic globalization in the dissemination of technology and power would be reversed, while the negative consequences of military and ecological globalization would be further consolidated, such as wars, terrorism, climate change, and the spread of infectious diseases.
If that is indeed the case, the flat world would become a desert.
